  "text": "The of the antigenic loss variants reported in the classic study [CITATION_1] , one was later proven to contain a mutation in the P1A epitope (position 7, V→A) [CITATION_2] . This mutation prevented the clone from being recognized by one, but not another, CTL clone specific for the same epitope [CITATION_3] . However, the authors reported that the tumor clone harboring this mutation had a significant growth advantage in vitro over other tumor cells in the same isolate [CITATION_4] . It is thus unclear whether this tumor variant was selected for in vivo, and if so, whether it was selected based on its lack of antigenicity. If both these questions were answered in the affirmative, it would indicate that antigenic drift in tumors can occur in mice with an unmanipulated T cell repertoire.",
